      "url": "https://api.github.com/users/thomasbuilds",
      "html_url": "https://github.com/thomasbuilds",
      "followers_url": "https://api.github.com/users/thomasbuilds/followers",
      "following_url": "https://api.github.com/users/thomasbuilds/following%7B/other_user%7D",
      "gists_url": "https://api.github.com/users/thomasbuilds/gists%7B/gist_id%7D",
      "starred_url": "https://api.github.com/users/thomasbuilds/starred%7B/owner%7D%7B/repo%7D",
      "subscriptions_url": "https://api.github.com/users/thomasbuilds/subscriptions",
      "organizations_url": "https://api.github.com/users/thomasbuilds/orgs",
      "repos_url": "https://api.github.com/users/thomasbuilds/repos",
      "events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/thomasbuilds/events%7B/privacy%7D",
      "received_events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/thomasbuilds/received_events",
      "type": "User",
      "site_admin": false,
      "name": null,
      "patch_url": null
    },
    "body": "`CHMAC_SHA256` and `CHMAC_SHA512` leave two stack buffers populated on return: `rkey[]` holds the inner-padded HMAC key (`K' ⊕ ipad`) at the end of the constructor, and `temp[]` holds the inner-hash output inside `Finalize()`. `rkey` is one constant XOR away from the key, so leaking it leaks the key.\r\n\r\nWhen the HMAC is keyed with sensitive material (BIP32 child key derivation in `key.cpp`, BIP324 transport keying via HKDF in `bip324.cpp`), this material persists on the stack until naturally overwritten.\r\n\r\nThis PR cleanses both buffers with `memory_cleanse()`, matching the convention already used in `chacha20.cpp` and `chacha20poly1305.cpp`. No observable change for callers; cost is two extra `memory_cleanse()` calls per HMAC computation.",
    "labels": [
