      "message": "crypto: cleanse HMAC stack buffers after use\n\nCHMAC_SHA256 and CHMAC_SHA512 leave two stack buffers populated on\nreturn: rkey[] holds the inner-padded HMAC key (K' XOR ipad) at the\nend of the constructor, and temp[] holds the inner-hash output\nH(K' XOR ipad || message), where H is the underlying SHA-256 or\nSHA-512, inside Finalize().\n\nrkey is the key with a constant XOR applied, so leaking it leaks the\nkey directly. temp is a one-way hash covering the key and message;\nleaking it does not recover the key but enables offline brute force\nagainst the key for that message.\n\nWhen the HMAC is keyed with sensitive material (e.g. BIP32 child key\nderivation in key.cpp, BIP324 transport keying via HKDF in bip324.cpp),\nthis stack data persists until naturally overwritten by subsequent\nframes.\n\nCleanse both buffers with memory_cleanse() before they go out of\nscope, matching the convention already used in chacha20.cpp and\nchacha20poly1305.cpp.\n\nCost is two extra memory_cleanse() calls per HMAC computation\n(memset + compiler barrier on Linux, SecureZeroMemory on Windows).\nNo observable change for callers.",
